{"title_page": "Egutu Oliseh", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Egutu Oliseh\n| fullname = Egutu Chukwuma Oliseh\n| height = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]]\n| \n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1998\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[AS Nancy|Nancy]]| caps1 = 46 |goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1999\u20132000 |clubs2 = \u2192 [[CS Louhans-Cuiseaux|Louhans-Cuiseaux]] (loan) | caps2 = 8  |goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002 |clubs3 = \u2192 [[AS Beauvais Oise|Beauvais]] (loan)| caps3 = 34 |goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2003\u20132005 |clubs4 = [[Grenoble Foot|Grenoble]]| caps4 = 51 |goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2005\u20132006 |clubs5 = [[R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise|La Louviere]]| caps5 = 31 |goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2006\u20132007 |clubs6 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] | caps6 = 2  |goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008 |clubs7 = [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]]| caps7 = 43 |goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 2008\u20132012 |clubs8 = [[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]| caps8 = 36 |goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2010\u20132012 |clubs9 = \u2192 [[Ergotelis F.C.|Ergotelis]] (loan)| caps9 = 47 |goals9 = 1\n| years10 = 2012\u20132013|clubs10 = [[Panachaiki F.C.|Panachaiki]]| caps10 = 13 |goals10 = 1\n| years11 = 2013\u20132014|clubs11 = [[Olympiakos Volou 1937 F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]]| caps11 = 37 |goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2014|clubs12 = [[Paniliakos F.C.|Paniliakos]]| caps12 = 7 |goals12 = 0\n| years13 = 2014\u20132015|clubs13 = [[Apollon 1926 F.C.|Apollon 1926]]| caps13 = 10 |goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2015\u20132017|clubs14 = [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]| caps14 = 14 |goals14 =\n}}\n\n'''Egutu Chukwuma Oliseh''' (born 18 November 1980) is a [[Nigeria]]n [[association football|footballer]] currently playing for [[Greece|Greek]] club [[Olympiakos Laurium F.C.]] in the amateur Football League of Eastern Attica (EPSANA) as a [[midfielder]]. Having experience from Belgian, French and English football in earlier years, he is considered a Greek football journeyman, as he already played for seven different teams in [[Greece]] since his first arrival in the country in 2008.\n\n==Career==\nOliseh started his career at [[AS Nancy|Nancy]]. He was loaned out twice during his 5-year spell with the club. He subsequently transferred to [[Grenoble Foot|Grenoble]] and [[R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise|La Louviere]], before joining the [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 2006. His stay at [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] was unremarkable though, as he was deemed to be surplus to requirements by manager [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]]. In January 2007, after only a six-month stay at the club, it was announced he had joined [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]]. After one season, he moved to newly promoted [[Greece|Greek]] side [[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]], in the [[Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]]. After the club's relegation to the [[Football League (Greece)|Football League]] in 2010, Oliseh was loaned out to [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]] side [[Ergotelis F.C.|Ergotelis]] for two years. After his loaning spell ended, he went on to play for [[Panachaiki F.C.|Panachaiki]], [[Olympiakos Volou 1937 F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]] and [[Paniliakos F.C.|Paniliakos]], all in the [[Football League (Greece)|Football League]]. On 30 July 2014 he joined [[Apollon 1926 F.C.|Apollon Kalamarias]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paeapollon1926.gr/678-katsiaros-kai-oliseh-oi-protoi|title=\u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Oliseh \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9|publisher=PAE Apollon|accessdate=31 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811122906/http://www.paeapollon1926.gr/678-katsiaros-kai-oliseh-oi-protoi|archivedate=11 August 2014}}</ref> and later on played for [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon]] and [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]] in the same tier of Greek football. On 3 January 2017, it was announced that Oliseh moved to amateur side [[Olympiakos Lavriou]] in Eastern Attica, making this transfer the biggest in the club's history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/podosfairo/bomba-apo-olumpiako-lauriou-ekane-ti-megaluteri-metagrafi-tis-istorias-tou/3254800|title=\"\u0392\u03cc\u03bc\u03b2\u03b1\" \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u039f\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03b1\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5: \u0388\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5!|newspaper=sport-fm.gr|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the younger brother of [[Churchill Oliseh]], [[Sunday Oliseh]] and [[Azubike Oliseh]]; his nephew is [[Sekou Oliseh]].\nHe also holds French passport.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway}}\n*{{LFP|id=oliseh-egutu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliseh, Egutu}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:AS Nancy players]]\n[[Category:Louhans-Cuiseaux FC players]]\n[[Category:AS Beauvais Oise players]]\n[[Category:Grenoble Foot 38 players]]\n[[Category:R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise players]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Montpellier HSC players]]\n[[Category:Panthrakikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ergotelis F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panachaiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos Volou 1937 F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Paniliakos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Egutu Oliseh\n| fullname = Egutu Chukwuma Oliseh\n| height = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]]\n| \n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1998\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[AS Nancy|Nancy]]| caps1 = 46 |goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1999\u20132000 |clubs2 = \u2192 [[CS Louhans-Cuiseaux|Louhans-Cuiseaux]] (loan) | caps2 = 8  |goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2001\u20132002 |clubs3 = \u2192 [[AS Beauvais Oise|Beauvais]] (loan)| caps3 = 34 |goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2003\u20132005 |clubs4 = [[Grenoble Foot|Grenoble]]| caps4 = 51 |goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2005\u20132006 |clubs5 = [[R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise|La Louviere]]| caps5 = 31 |goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2006\u20132007 |clubs6 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] | caps6 = 2  |goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008 |clubs7 = [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]]| caps7 = 43 |goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 2008\u20132012 |clubs8 = [[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]| caps8 = 36 |goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2010\u20132012 |clubs9 = \u2192 [[Ergotelis F.C.|Ergotelis]] (loan)| caps9 = 47 |goals9 = 1\n| years10 = 2012\u20132013|clubs10 = [[Panachaiki F.C.|Panachaiki]]| caps10 = 13 |goals10 = 1\n| years11 = 2013\u20132014|clubs11 = [[Olympiakos Volou 1937 F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]]| caps11 = 37 |goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2014|clubs12 = [[Paniliakos F.C.|Paniliakos]]| caps12 = 7 |goals12 = 0\n| years13 = 2014\u20132015|clubs13 = [[Apollon 1926 F.C.|Apollon 1926]]| caps13 = 10 |goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2015\u20132017|clubs14 = [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]| caps14 = 14 |goals14 =\n}}\n\n'''Egutu Chukwuma Oliseh''' (born 18 November 1980) is a [[Nigeria]]n [[association football|footballer]] currently playing for [[Greece|Greek]] club [[Olympiakos Laurium F.C.]] in the amateur Football League of Eastern Attica (EPSANA) as a [[midfielder]]. Having experience from Belgian, French and English football in earlier years, he is considered a Greek football journeyman, as he already played for seven different teams in [[Greece]] since his first arrival in the country in 2008.\n\n==Career==\nOliseh started his career at [[AS Nancy|Nancy]]. He was loaned out twice during his 5-year spell with the club. He subsequently transferred to [[Grenoble Foot|Grenoble]] and [[R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise|La Louviere]], before joining the [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] in 2006. His stay at [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] was unremarkable though, as he was deemed to be surplus to requirements by manager [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]]. In January 2007, after only a six-month stay at the club, it was announced he had joined [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]]. After one season, he moved to newly promoted [[Greece|Greek]] side [[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]], in the [[Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]]. After the club's relegation to the [[Football League (Greece)|Football League]] in 2010, Oliseh was loaned out to [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]] side [[Ergotelis F.C.|Ergotelis]] for two years. After his loaning spell ended, he went on to play for [[Panachaiki F.C.|Panachaiki]], [[Olympiakos Volou 1937 F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]] and [[Paniliakos F.C.|Paniliakos]], all in the [[Football League (Greece)|Football League]]. On 30 July 2014 he joined [[Apollon 1926 F.C.|Apollon Kalamarias]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paeapollon1926.gr/678-katsiaros-kai-oliseh-oi-protoi|title=\u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 Oliseh \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9|publisher=PAE Apollon|accessdate=31 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811122906/http://www.paeapollon1926.gr/678-katsiaros-kai-oliseh-oi-protoi|archivedate=11 August 2014}}</ref> and later on played for [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon]] and [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]] in the same tier of Greek football. On 3 January 2017, it was announced that Oliseh moved to amateur side [[Olympiakos Lavriou]] in Eastern Attica, making this transfer the biggest in the club's history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/podosfairo/bomba-apo-olumpiako-lauriou-ekane-ti-megaluteri-metagrafi-tis-istorias-tou/3254800|title=\"\u0392\u03cc\u03bc\u03b2\u03b1\" \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u039f\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03b1\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5: \u0388\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5!|newspaper=sport-fm.gr|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the younger brother of [[Churchill Oliseh]], [[Sunday Oliseh]] and [[Azubike Oliseh]]; his nephew is [[Sekou Oliseh]].\nHe also holds French passport.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=59123 Scoresway.com Profile]\n*{{LFP|id=oliseh-egutu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliseh, Egutu}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:AS Nancy players]]\n[[Category:Louhans-Cuiseaux FC players]]\n[[Category:AS Beauvais Oise players]]\n[[Category:Grenoble Foot 38 players]]\n[[Category:R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise players]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Montpellier HSC players]]\n[[Category:Panthrakikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ergotelis F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panachaiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos Volou 1937 F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Paniliakos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egutu_Oliseh"}
{"title_page": "Feminist performance art", "text_new": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n==[[Yoko Ono]]==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as John Lennon\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the Beatles grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "text_old": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n== Yoko Ono ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as John Lennon\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the Beatles grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "name_user": "EMVRay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a hyperlink to yoko ono", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feminist_performance_art"}
{"title_page": "1987 Alianza Lima plane crash", "text_new": "{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name          = 1987 Alianza Lima air disaster\n|image         = Algerian Air Force Fokker F-27-400M Troopship Goetting-1.jpg\n|caption       = A Fokker F27-400M, the aircraft type involved in the accident\n|date          = 8 December 1987\n|type          = Pilot error\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site          = [[Ventanilla District]], [[Peru]]\n|coords        =  {{Coord|-11.967|-77.160|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|aircraft_type = [[Fokker F27]]\n|aircraft_name =\n|operator      = [[Peruvian Navy|Servicio Aeronaval de la Marina del Peru]] (charter)\n|tail_number   = AE-560\n|origin        = [[FAP Captain David Abenzur Rengifo International Airport]]\n|stopover      =\n|destination   = [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]]\n|occupants     = 44\n|passengers    = 38\n|crew          = 6\n|injuries      =\n|fatalities    = 43\n|survivors     = 1 (initially 2)\n}}\n\nThe '''1987 Alianza Lima air disaster''' occurred on 8 December 1987, when a Peruvian Navy [[Fokker F27]]-400M chartered by [[Peru]]vian [[association football|football]] club [[Alianza Lima]] crashed into the [[Pacific Ocean]] seven miles from [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]] near the city of [[Callao]]. Of the 44 people on board, only the pilot survived. \n\nThe Peruvian Naval Aviation Commission investigated the accident and created a report but never officially disclosed its content. Eventually, the Navy's accident report was discovered and details of it were released. In the report, investigators cited pilot error as the primary cause of the accident. \n\n==Accident==\nAlianza was scheduled to play a football match against Deportivo Pucallpa and had organized a charter aircraft, provided by the Air Services branch of the [[Peruvian Navy]] for the trip to Pucallpa and back. After the game the aircraft departed Pucallpa at 6:30 p.m. with Peruvian Navy Lieutenant Edilberto Villar as the [[pilot in command]], C\u00e9sar Morales as copilot, four cabin crewmembers and 38 players, staff and team supporters.<ref name=\"avi\"/>\n\nThe flight was uneventful until the crew began their descent into Lima. Upon lowering the landing gear, the left and right main gear displayed green lights, indicating down and locked, but the nose gear did not. Villar requested that Morales consult the flight manual for the proper procedure to follow. The manual was written in English and because Morales's foreign language skill was poor he read out the wrong procedure. The crew requested a fly-by of the control tower so that observers could confirm that the nose gear was down. Using binoculars the observers confirmed that the airplane was configured for landing and the crew brought the aircraft around for another attempt at a landing. While over water the aircraft flew too low and the right wing struck the surface of the ocean as the aircraft was lining up with the runway, {{convert|6.9|mi|disp=flip|abbr=on}} northwest of the airport. The airliner broke up on impact and the forward fuselage sank.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |title=42 Believed Dead in Peru Crash; Star Soccer Team Among Victims |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/10/world/42-believed-dead-in-peru-crash-star-soccer-team-among-victims.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"avi\">{{cite web |title=Tuesday 8 December 1987 |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |website=aviation-saftey.net |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"per\">{{cite web |title=New revelations about plane crash killing Peruvian football team 19 years ago |url=https://archive.is/20061028064903/http://www.livinginperu.com/news/2562 |website=www.livinginperu.com |publisher=Peru Experience |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Aircraft==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Fokker F27|Fokker F27-400M Friendship]], [[aircraft registration|registration]] AE-560. The airliner, with [[serial number]] 10548, had first flown in 1977 and had logged a total of 5,908 hours.<ref name=\"avi\"/>\n\n==Passengers==\nAlianza lost the majority of its team as a result of the accident. Notable passengers on the flight included:<ref>{{cite web |last1=Orrego |first1=Daniel |title=30 a\u00f1os de la tragedia de Alianza Lima: Treinta a\u00f1os de galope eterno |url=https://dechalaca.com/informes/estadisticas/treinta-anos-de-galope-eterno |website=dechalaca.com |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Casanova Mendoza|Jos\u00e9 Casanova]]\n*[[Luis Antonio Escobar (footballer)|Luis Antonio Escobar]]\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez Ganoza]]\n*[[Alfredo Tomassini]]\n*[[Johnny Watson (footballer)|Johnny Watson]]\n*[[Marcos Calder\u00f3n]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe pilot and sole survivor Villar was able to exit the aircraft from a hole in the fuselage and ascend to the surface where he was joined by soccer player Alfredo Tomasini. Villar was able to trap air in some clothing to use as a flotation devise. Tomasini was suffering from a broken leg and other injuries. The pilot and athlete floated together for hours but near sunrise the two became separated in the choppy waters and Tomasini drowned. Shortly after dawn, search and rescue teams discovered the aircraft tail section floating and rescued Villar after more than 11 hours in the water.<ref name=\"apn\">{{cite web |last1=Seavey |first1=Robert |title=Ocean Search Resumes for Plane Crash Victims |url=https://apnews.com/95f631e5db68ec8cef81bda4b6ca3971 |website=apnews.com |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe accident was announced to a stunned community and over the next several days some bodies were recovered from the sea.<ref name=\"tft\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Ian |title=The Alianza Lima air disaster of 1987 |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/09/15/the-alianza-lima-air-disaster-of-1987/ |website=thesefootballtimes.co |publisher=These Football Times |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation ==\nFollowing the crash the Peruvian Navy refused to make any statements concerning the cause of the accident.The Peruvian Naval Aviation Commission allowed no private investigations to take place and began its own investigation. An accident report was made but not released to the public.<ref name=\"tft\"/>  \n\nIn 2006 producers working on a story for Peruvian television program ''La Ventana Indiscreta'' uncovered the Navy report which had been illegally locked in a Florida deposit box for 18 years. The investigation cited the pilot's lack of night flying experience, the co-pilots misreading of the emergency procedures related to the landing gear issue, and the aircraft's poor mechanical condition as contributing factors to the accident.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\nAccording to the report, dated February 1988, Lieutenant Villar had logged just 5.3 hours of night flying in the 90 days preceding the accident, 3.3 of them in the previous 60 days, and had not flown at night in at least 30 days before the crash. The copilot, First Lieutenant C\u00e9sar Morales, had logged only one hour of night flying in the 90 days preceding the accident, half an hour in the preceding 60 days, and had also not flown at night in at least 30 days. Additionally, the F27's maintenance log, which was handed to the pilot before takeoff, showed a series of mechanical defects including lacking an inertial guidance system, poor [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio performance, a [[VHF omnidirectional range|VOR receiving unit]] with inadequate reception, a malfunctioning [[radar altimeter]] and a worn front landing gear indicator light switch. Lieutenant Villar initially refused to fly the aircraft out of concern for its condition.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref name=\"avi\"/><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\nIn a letter from the [[Fokker]] aircraft company, dated October 16, 1986, the manufacturer noted that Lieutenant Villar had failed a special training course which could have prevented \u201chis disorientation while operating under pressure, the excessive demand of work in a cabin\u201d, but was granted permission to fly the aircraft regardless. Copilot C\u00e9sar Morales had received no flight training from Fokker.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Accident Database: Accident Synopsis 12081987 |url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=12081987&reg=AE-560&airline=Servicio+Aeronaval+de+Peru |work= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7E0cf0?url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=12081987&reg=AE-560&airline=Servicio+Aeronaval+de+Peru |archivedate=2009-08-05 |url-status=live |accessdate=2009-08-02 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of accidents involving sports teams]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.flacso.org.ec/docs/i25panfichi.pdf\n*{{cite web|url=http://es.geocities.com/futbolenlared2003/potrillos.htm |title=EN LA GLORIA. POTRILLOS DEL 87 |work=Yahoo Small Business |accessdate=28 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7EM1JC?url=http://es.geocities.com/futbolenlared2003/potrillos.htm |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df= }}( 2009-08-05)\n*{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-27 Friendship 400M AE-560 Lima-Jorge Chavez International Airport (LIM) |date=8 December 1987 |publisher= |accessdate=28 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7GHP25?url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df= }}( 2009-08-05)\n* {{cite web |url=https://dechalaca.com/informes/estadisticas/treinta-anos-de-galope-eterno |title=30 a\u00f1os de la tragedia de Alianza Lima: Treinta a\u00f1os de galope eterno |language=Spanish |first=Daniel |last=Orrego |date=8 December 2017 |accessdate=16 February 2019}}\n\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 1987}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alianza Lima Air Disaster}}\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Peru]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1987]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Fokker F27]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents involving professional sports teams]]\n[[Category:1987 in Peru]]\n[[Category:1987 in Peruvian football]]\n[[Category:December 1987 events in South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name          = 1987 Alianza Lima air disaster\n|image         = Algerian Air Force Fokker F-27-400M Troopship Goetting-1.jpg\n|caption       = A Fokker F27-400M, the aircraft type involved in the accident\n|date          = 8 December 1987\n|type          = Pilot error\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site          = [[Ventanilla District]], [[Peru]]\n|coords        =  {{Coord|-11.967|-77.160|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|aircraft_type = [[Fokker F27]]\n|aircraft_name =\n|operator      = [[Peruvian Navy|Servicio Aeronaval de la Marina del Peru]] (charter)\n|tail_number   = AE-560\n|origin        = [[FAP Captain David Abenzur Rengifo International Airport]]\n|stopover      =\n|destination   = [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]]\n|occupants     = 44\n|passengers    = 38\n|crew          = 6\n|injuries      =\n|fatalities    = 43\n|survivors     = 1\n}}\n\nThe '''1987 Alianza Lima air disaster''' occurred on 8 December 1987, when a Peruvian Navy [[Fokker F27]]-400M chartered by [[Peru]]vian [[association football|football]] club [[Alianza Lima]] crashed into the [[Pacific Ocean]] seven miles from [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport]] near the city of [[Callao]]. Of the 44 people on board only the pilot survived. \n\nThe Peruvian Naval Aviation Commission investigated the accident and created a report but never officially disclosed its content. Eventually the Navy's accident report was discovered and details of it were released. In the report, investigators cited pilot error as the primary cause of the accident. \n\n==Accident==\nAlianza was scheduled to play a football match against Deportivo Pucallpa and had organized a charter aircraft, provided by the Air Services branch of the [[Peruvian Navy]] for the trip to Pucallpa and back. After the game the aircraft departed Pucallpa at 6:30 p.m. with Peruvian Navy Lieutenant Edilberto Villar as the [[pilot in command]], C\u00e9sar Morales as copilot, four cabin crewmembers and 38 players, staff and team supporters.<ref name=\"avi\"/>\n\nThe flight was uneventful until the crew began their descent into Lima. Upon lowering the landing gear, the left and right main gear displayed green lights, indicating down and locked, but the nose gear did not. Villar requested that Morales consult the flight manual for the proper procedure to follow. The manual was written in English and because Morales's foreign language skill was poor he read out the wrong procedure. The crew requested a fly-by of the control tower so that observers could confirm that the nose gear was down. Using binoculars the observers confirmed that the airplane was configured for landing and the crew brought the aircraft around for another attempt at a landing. While over water the aircraft flew too low and the right wing struck the surface of the ocean as the aircraft was lining up with the runway, {{convert|6.9|mi|disp=flip|abbr=on}} northwest of the airport. The airliner broke up on impact and the forward fuselage sank.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |title=42 Believed Dead in Peru Crash; Star Soccer Team Among Victims |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/10/world/42-believed-dead-in-peru-crash-star-soccer-team-among-victims.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"avi\">{{cite web |title=Tuesday 8 December 1987 |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |website=aviation-saftey.net |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"per\">{{cite web |title=New revelations about plane crash killing Peruvian football team 19 years ago |url=https://archive.is/20061028064903/http://www.livinginperu.com/news/2562 |website=www.livinginperu.com |publisher=Peru Experience |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Aircraft==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Fokker F27|Fokker F27-400M Friendship]], [[aircraft registration|registration]] AE-560. The airliner, with [[serial number]] 10548, had first flown in 1977 and had logged a total of 5,908 hours.<ref name=\"avi\"/>\n\n==Passengers==\nAlianza lost the majority of its team as a result of the accident. Notable passengers on the flight included:<ref>{{cite web |last1=Orrego |first1=Daniel |title=30 a\u00f1os de la tragedia de Alianza Lima: Treinta a\u00f1os de galope eterno |url=https://dechalaca.com/informes/estadisticas/treinta-anos-de-galope-eterno |website=dechalaca.com |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Casanova Mendoza|Jos\u00e9 Casanova]]\n*[[Luis Antonio Escobar (footballer)|Luis Antonio Escobar]]\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez Ganoza]]\n*[[Alfredo Tomassini]]\n*[[Johnny Watson (footballer)|Johnny Watson]]\n*[[Marcos Calder\u00f3n]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe pilot and sole survivor Villar was able to exit the aircraft from a hole in the fuselage and ascend to the surface where he was joined by soccer player Alfredo Tomasini. Villar was able to trap air in some clothing to use as a flotation devise. Tomasini was suffering from a broken leg and other injuries. The pilot and athlete floated together for hours but near sunrise the two became separated in the choppy waters and Tomasini drowned. shortly after dawn search and rescue teams discovered the aircraft tail section floating and rescued Villar after more than 11 hours in the water.<ref name=\"apn\">{{cite web |last1=Seavey |first1=Robert |title=Ocean Search Resumes for Plane Crash Victims |url=https://apnews.com/95f631e5db68ec8cef81bda4b6ca3971 |website=apnews.com |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe accident was announced to a stunned community and over the next several days some bodies were recovered from the sea.<ref name=\"tft\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Ian |title=The Alianza Lima air disaster of 1987 |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/09/15/the-alianza-lima-air-disaster-of-1987/ |website=thesefootballtimes.co |publisher=These Football Times |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation ==\nFollowing the crash the Peruvian Navy refused to make any statements concerning the cause of the accident.The Peruvian Naval Aviation Commission allowed no private investigations to take place and began its own investigation. An accident report was made but not released to the public.<ref name=\"tft\"/>  \n\nIn 2006 producers working on a story for Peruvian television program ''La Ventana Indiscreta'' uncovered the Navy report which had been illegally locked in a Florida deposit box for 18 years. The investigation cited the pilot's lack of night flying experience, the co-pilots misreading of the emergency procedures related to the landing gear issue, and the aircraft's poor mechanical condition as contributing factors to the accident.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\nAccording to the report, dated February 1988, Lieutenant Villar had logged just 5.3 hours of night flying in the 90 days preceding the accident, 3.3 of them in the previous 60 days, and had not flown at night in at least 30 days before the crash. The copilot, First Lieutenant C\u00e9sar Morales, had logged only one hour of night flying in the 90 days preceding the accident, half an hour in the preceding 60 days, and had also not flown at night in at least 30 days. Additionally, the F27's maintenance log, which was handed to the pilot before takeoff, showed a series of mechanical defects including lacking an inertial guidance system, poor [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] radio performance, a [[VHF omnidirectional range|VOR receiving unit]] with inadequate reception, a malfunctioning [[radar altimeter]] and a worn front landing gear indicator light switch. Lieutenant Villar initially refused to fly the aircraft out of concern for its condition.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref name=\"avi\"/><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\nIn a letter from the [[Fokker]] aircraft company, dated October 16, 1986, the manufacturer noted that Lieutenant Villar had failed a special training course which could have prevented \u201chis disorientation while operating under pressure, the excessive demand of work in a cabin\u201d, but was granted permission to fly the aircraft regardless. Copilot C\u00e9sar Morales had received no flight training from Fokker.<ref name=\"per\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Accident Database: Accident Synopsis 12081987 |url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=12081987&reg=AE-560&airline=Servicio+Aeronaval+de+Peru |work= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7E0cf0?url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=12081987&reg=AE-560&airline=Servicio+Aeronaval+de+Peru |archivedate=2009-08-05 |url-status=live |accessdate=2009-08-02 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"tft\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of accidents involving sports teams]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.flacso.org.ec/docs/i25panfichi.pdf\n*{{cite web|url=http://es.geocities.com/futbolenlared2003/potrillos.htm |title=EN LA GLORIA. POTRILLOS DEL 87 |work=Yahoo Small Business |accessdate=28 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7EM1JC?url=http://es.geocities.com/futbolenlared2003/potrillos.htm |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df= }}( 2009-08-05)\n*{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-27 Friendship 400M AE-560 Lima-Jorge Chavez International Airport (LIM) |date=8 December 1987 |publisher= |accessdate=28 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5io7GHP25?url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df= }}( 2009-08-05)\n* {{cite web |url=https://dechalaca.com/informes/estadisticas/treinta-anos-de-galope-eterno |title=30 a\u00f1os de la tragedia de Alianza Lima: Treinta a\u00f1os de galope eterno |language=Spanish |first=Daniel |last=Orrego |date=8 December 2017 |accessdate=16 February 2019}}\n\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 1987}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alianza Lima Air Disaster}}\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Peru]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1987]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Fokker F27]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents involving professional sports teams]]\n[[Category:1987 in Peru]]\n[[Category:1987 in Peruvian football]]\n[[Category:December 1987 events in South America]]\n", "name_user": "Why can't I edit Userpedia?", "label": "safe", "comment": "Capitalization and punctuation fixes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987_Alianza_Lima_plane_crash"}
